-period-in-punjab-review/ |title=Patta-Patta Singhan Da Vairi revolves around police atrocities of post-1984 period in Punjab |date=18 April 2015 |work=Sikh Siyasat News |access-date=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420184140/http://sikhsiyasat.net/2015/04/18/patta-patta-singhan-da-vairi-revolves-around-police-atrocities-of-post-1984-period-in-punjab-review/ |archive-date=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n| ''[[The Mastermind Jinda Sukha]]''\n| The film was cleared by the CBFC but banned by the [[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Minister of Home Affairs]]. The films is based on the lives of the assassins of General [[Arun Shridhar Vaidya]]. The makers of the film decided to release it overseas.<ref name=\"ReleaseAbroad-HT\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/chandigarh/jinda-sukha-banned-in-india-film-makers-to-release-it-abroad/story-8RXZyW7LBlhWsxhnUzMblL.html |title='Jinda-Sukha' banned in India, film makers to release it abroad |date=13 September 2015 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307132119/http://www.hindustantimes.com/chandigarh/jinda-sukha-banned-in-india-film-makers-to-release-it-abroad/story-8RXZyW7LBlhWsxhnUzMblL.html |archive-date=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Painted House]]''\n| The CBFC denied a rating to film for containing nudity. They suggested the scenes should be blurred or deleted.<ref name=\"DepictingNudity-TOI\">{{Cite news |url=http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31811&articlexml=Film-denied-certificate-for-depicting-nudity-25082015004061 |title=Film denied certificate for depicting nudity |date=25 August 2015 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006162408/http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31811&articlexml=Film-denied-certificate-for-depicting-nudity-25082015004061 |archive-date=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Mohalla Assi]]''\n| The CBFC denied a rating to the film. The film deals with the commercialisation of the pilgrimage city [[Varanasi]].<ref name=\"Sunny-Starrer\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Censors-refuses-certificate-to-Sunny-starrer/articleshow/51736224.cms |title=Censors refuses certificate to Sunny starrer |date=8 April 2016 |work=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |access-date=8 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414120035/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/bollywood/Censors-refuses-certificate-to-Sunny-starrer/articleshow/51736224.cms |archive-date=14 April 2016}}</ref> On December 11, 2017, Delhi High Court allowed the release of the film with one cut and adult certification, setting aside the order of CBFC.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://barandbench.com/delhi-hc-allows-mohalla-assi-release/ |title=Delhi HC allows release of film Mohalla Assi with Adult Certificate {{!}} Bar & Bench |website=Bar & Bench |access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Regional ==\n\n=== Provinces of British India ===\n* 1921 \u2013 ''[[Bhakta Vidur]]'': Banned in Karachi and [[Madras Presidency|Madras]] for political reasons.<ref name=\"Woods2011\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jw-2w-SpuZMC&pg=PA98 |title=Visions of Empire and Other Imaginings: Cinema, Ireland and India 1910\u20131962 |last=Jeannine Woods |publisher=Peter Lang |year=2011 |isbn=978-3-03911-974-5 |page=98 |access-date=17 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004728/http://books.google.com/books?id=Jw-2w-SpuZMC&pg=PA98 |archive-date=2 May 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> the film came right after [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]] and [[Rowlatt Act]]. The character [[Vidura]] was moulded upon personality of [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref name=\"Dwyer2006\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8qjKJ0yk-gQC&pg=PA72 |title=Filming the Gods: Religion and Indian Cinema |last=Rachel Dwyer |date=30 August 2006 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-203-08865-4 |pages=72\u2013 |access-date=18 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002325/http://books.google.com/books?id=8qjKJ0yk-gQC&pg=PA72 |archive-date=2 May 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1939 \u2013 ''[[Thyagabhoomi]]'': Banned in [[Madras Presidency|Madras]], 22 weeks after release for supporting [[Indian National Congress|Congress]], [[Indian independence movement|independence movement]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2008/03/21/stories/2008032150321600.htm |title=Blast from the past |last=Guy |first=Randor |date=2008-03-21 |work=The Hindu |access-date=2013-07-26 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108170427/http://www.hindu.com/cp/2008/03/21/stories/2008032150321600.htm |archive-date=8 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Andhra Pradesh ===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]'': It was banned after some Christians and Muslims who took offence protested.<ref name=\"VinciAndhra\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/06/02/stories/2006060207640600.htm |title=`The Da Vinci Code' banned in Andhra Pradesh |date=2 June 2006 |work=The Hindu |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422204751/http://www.hindu.com/2006/06/02/stories/2006060207640600.htm |archive-date=22 April 2008}}</ref> Later, the ban was lifted by the [[High Court of Judicature at Hyderabad|Andhra Pradesh High Court]].<ref name=\"VinciAndhraHC\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-22/hyderabad/27794062_1_quashes-film-expert-body |title=HC quashes ban on Da Vinci Code |date=22 June 2006 |work=The Times of India |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225165605/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-22/hyderabad/27794062_1_quashes-film-expert-body |archive-date=25 December 2013}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Aarakshan]]'': It was banned on 11 August 2011 due to concerns that it may hurt weaker sections of the society.<ref name=\"APAar\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1574946/report-now-andhra-pradesh-bans-aarakshan |title=Now, Andhra Pradesh bans Aarakshan |date=11 August 2011 |work=[[DNA India]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref> On 14 August 2011, the ban was revoked.<ref name=\"APAar2\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-08-14/india/29886448_1_aarakshan-ban-statewide-ban-prakash-jha-s-aarakshan |title=AP, Punjab lift Aarakshan ban |date=14 August 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Assam ===\n* 1952 \u2013 ''[[Runumi]]'': The film was suddenly banned by then [[Government of Assam]] headed by chief minister [[Bishnuram Medhi]] due to some unknown reason.<ref name=\"ab\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.assamtribune.com/scripts/detailsnew.asp?id=mar1510/at09 |title=Lost treasure of Assamese cinema retrieved |last=Staff Reporter |date=14 March 2010 |publisher=The Assam Tribune |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304010531/http://www.assamtribune.com/scripts/detailsnew.asp?id=mar1510%2Fat09 |archive-date=4 March 2012 |access-date=28 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"cd\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/guwahati/Banned-in-1952-Assamese-film-pops-up-to-ask-questions/Article1-519190.aspx |title=Banned 1952, Assamese film pops up to ask question |last=Karmakar |first=Rahul |date=15 March 2010 |publisher=Hinsustan Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325065100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/guwahati/Banned-in-1952-Assamese-film-pops-up-to-ask-questions/Article1-519190.aspx |archive-date=25 March 2010 |access-date=28 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ef\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/03/15/stories/2010031556592200.htm |title=Film print returns to family after four decades |last=Talukdar |first=Sushanta |date=15 March 2010 |publisher=The Hindu |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323005358/http://www.hindu.com/2010/03/15/stories/2010031556592200.htm |archive-date=23 March 2010 |access-date=28 March 2010}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 ''[[Tango Charlie]]'': The film was allegedly poorly researched and defamed the [[Bodo people|Bodo]] community.<ref name=\"Tango\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/14152.html |title='Tango Charlie' banned in Assam |last=Zarir Hussain |first=Syed |publisher=IndiaGlitz |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621190718/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/14152.html |archive-date=21 June 2013 |access-date=7 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Chhattisgarh ===\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[MSG-2 The Messenger]]'' :Film was banned in [[Chhattisgarh]]<ref name=\"http://www.hindustantimes.com/ 2015\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/msg-2-banned-in-chattisgarh-film-refers-to-tribals-as-shaitan/article1-1391572.aspx |title=MSG 2 banned in Chattisgarh; film refers to tribals as 'shaitan' |date=19 September 2015 |website=www.hindustantimes.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921081201/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/msg-2-banned-in-chattisgarh-film-refers-to-tribals-as-shaitan/article1-1391572.aspx |archive-date=21 September 2015 |access-date=19 September 2015}}</ref> for hurting sentiments of [[Adivasi]] community (Tribal community).<ref name=\"PTI 2015\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Tribal-Activist-Moves-HC-to-Ban-MSG-2-The-Messenger/2015/09/18/article3034920.ece |title=Tribal Activist Moves HC to Ban 'MSG 2: The Messenger' |last=PTI |date=19 September 2015 |website=The New Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001204929/http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Tribal-Activist-Moves-HC-to-Ban-MSG-2-The-Messenger/2015/09/18/article3034920.ece |archive-date=1 October 2015 |access-date=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Goa ===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]'': It was banned considering \"public sentiments\" after protests by Christian organisations.<ref name=\"Goa1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/NM11/Goa-government-bans-Da-Vinci-Code/Article1-105881.aspx |title=Goa government bans Da Vinci Code |date=5 June 2006 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Goa2\">{{Cite news |url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/news/fullstory.php?newsid=68736 |title=Goa bans The Da Vinci Code |date=5 June 2006 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Gujarat ===\n* 2005 \u2013 ''Chand Bhuj Gaya'': This film which was set with the [[Godhra train burning]] as a backdrop was not released in Gujarat.<ref name=\"Chand\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2005/03/11/stories/2005031101570300.htm |title=Waiting for the moon |date=11 March 2005 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616143053/http://www.hindu.com/fr/2005/03/11/stories/2005031101570300.htm |archive-date=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[Fanaa (2006 film)|Fanaa]]'': It faced an unofficial ban due to the role of [[Aamir Khan]], the lead actor, in the [[Narmada Bachao Andolan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldpress.org/Asia/2380.cfm |title='Fanaa' a Hit Movie Despite Protests |last=Srinath |first=M.G. |website=Article on web |publisher=www.worldpress.org |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814075732/http://www.worldpress.org/Asia/2380.cfm |archive-date=14 August 2011 |access-date=12 August 2011}}</ref> Supreme Court of India directed that theatres wanting to screen the film should be provided police protection. But, most theatre owners decided not to screen it.<ref name=\"Fanaa\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-05/india/27823182_1_multiplex-owners-association-fanaa-anti-narmada |title=Gujarat unwilling to screen 'Fanaa' |date=5 June 2006 |work=The Times of India |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2007 \u2013 ''[[Parzania]]'': Parzania faced an unofficial ban after [[Bajrang Dal]] coaxed theatre owners to stop screening the film. Bajrang Dal activist [[Babu Bajrangi]], who was later incarcerated for murder, conspiracy and spreading hatred in [[Naroda Patiya massacre]] of Gujarat riots, had the opinion that it may disrupt communal harmony in the state.<ref name=\"Parzania\">{{Cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/qotd--why-ban-parzania-in-guj/33112-8.html |title=Gujarat multiplexes give in to Bajrang Dal, will not screen riot-film Parzania |date=6 February 2007 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2009 \u2013 ''[[Firaaq]]'': Firaaq was allegedly not released by many theatres due to political pressure because it depicted the [[2002 Gujarat riots]]. But, theatre owners cited a revenue sharing dispute.<ref name=\"firaaq\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=656215 |title=Nandita Das 'Firaaq' Banned in Gujarat Multiplexes |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130615180458/http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=656215 |archive-date=15 June 2013 |access-date=7 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"firaaq2\">{{Cite news |url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/latest-news/all-but-two-multiplex-groups-to-screen-firaaq-in-gujarat/436749/ |title=All but two multiplex groups to screen Firaaq in Gujarat |date=20 March 2009 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130807084320/http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/latest-news/all-but-two-multiplex-groups-to-screen-firaaq-in-gujarat/436749/ |archive-date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 ''[[Padmaavat]]'': Following controversies and threats of violence made by Rajput caste organization ''Shri Rajput Karni Sena''.<ref name=\"Padmaavat ban 2017\">{{Cite web |url=https://in.yahoo.com/style/padmaavat-row-haryana-cm-announces-114318071.html |title=Padmaavat Row: Haryana CM announces a ban on the film |last=Kanabar |first=Nirali |publisher=Yahoo! Lifestyle |access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Haryana ===\n* 2017 \u2013 ''[[Padmaavat]]'': Following controversies and threats of violence made by Rajput caste organization ''Shri Rajput Karni Sena''.<ref name=\"Padmaavat ban 2017\" />\n\n=== Jharkhand ===\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[MSG-2 The Messenger]]'' : Film was banned in [[Jharkhand]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/jharkhand-bans-msg-2-the-messenger/ |title=Jharkhand bans \u2018MSG 2 \u2013 The Messenger\u2019 |last=India |date=19 September 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001071310/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/jharkhand-bans-msg-2-the-messenger/ |archive-date=1 October 2015 |access-date=19 September 2015}}</ref> for hurting sentiments of [[Adivasi]] community (Tribal community).<ref name=\"PTI 2015\" />\n\n=== Kerala ===\n* 2012 \u2013 ''[[Pithavinum Puthranum]] '': The film originally completed in 2012 is awaiting approval from the Censor Board as of January 2015.<ref name=\"TwoYearsCensorBoard\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Two-years-on-Malayalam-film-awaits-Censor-Board-clearance/articleshow/45776647.cms |title=Two years on, Malayalam film awaits Censor Board clearance |date=6 January 2015 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=9 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110062055/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Two-years-on-Malayalam-film-awaits-Censor-Board-clearance/articleshow/45776647.cms |archive-date=10 January 2015}}</ref> The film was reported based on a book by [[Sister Jesme]] and the [[Sister Abhaya murder case]].<ref name=\"Pithavinum\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/censors-refuse-to-give-the-nod-for-pithavinum-puthranum-news-malayalam-ngnlEIjgcibsi.html |title=Censors refuse to give the nod for 'Pithavinum Puthranum'! |date=13 June 2013 |work=[[Sify]] |access-date=9 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422141953/http://www.sify.com/movies/censors-refuse-to-give-the-nod-for-pithavinum-puthranum-news-malayalam-ngnlEIjgcibsi.html |archive-date=22 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[The Painted House|Chayam Poosiya Veedu]]'' : The film was not given a certificate since there was a nude scene in it.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/directors-out-against-cbfc-directives/article7598642.ece |title=Directors out against CBFC directives |date=31 August 2015 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Madhya Pradesh ===\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Jodhaa Akbar]]'': The film was banned after protests from the [[Rajput]] community over [[Taj Bibi Bilqis Makani|Jodha Bai]]'s depiction as [[Akbar]]'s wife.<ref name=\"jodha\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Jodhaa-Akbar+banned+in+Madhya+Pradesh/1/4902.html |title=Jodhaa-Akbar banned in Madhya Pradesh |date=22 February 2008 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=7 May 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121035458/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Jodhaa-Akbar+banned+in+Madhya+Pradesh/1/4902.html |archive-date=21 November 2011}}</ref> The Supreme Court later lifted the ban.<ref name=\"SCJodhaa\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/supreme-court-lifts-ban-on-jodhaa-akbar/280412/ |title=Supreme Court lifts ban on Jodhaa Akbar |date=4 March 2008 |work=[[Indian Express]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[MSG-2 The Messenger]]'': The film was banned as it was an insult to [[Adivasi]]s (Tribals).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/msg-2-the-messenger-banned-in-madhya-pradesh/ |title=\u2018MSG-2 The Messenger\u2019 banned in Madhya Pradesh |last=India |date=26 September 2015 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028143614/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/msg-2-the-messenger-banned-in-madhya-pradesh/ |archive-date=28 October 2015 |access-date=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"IBNLive 2015\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/india/after-jharkhand-and-chattisgarh-madhya-pradesh-government-bans-msg-2-1112903.html |title=After Jharkhand and Chhattisgarh, Madhya Pradesh government bans 'MSG 2' |date=25 September 2015 |website=IBNLive |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926102758/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/india/after-jharkhand-and-chattisgarh-madhya-pradesh-government-bans-msg-2-1112903.html |archive-date=26 September 2015 |access-date=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Maharashtra ===\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Deshdrohi]]'': The film was banned in November fearing breakdown of law and order in the state. The film depicted the [[2008 attacks on Uttar Pradeshi and Bihari migrants in Maharashtra|attacks against North Indians]] in the state.<ref name=\"desh1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/nov/12film-deshdrohi-banned-in-maharashtra.htm |title=Maharashtra bans Deshdrohi |last=Ashraf |first=Syed Firdaus |publisher=[[Rediff]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065311/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/nov/12film-deshdrohi-banned-in-maharashtra.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |access-date=7 May 2013}}</ref> The ban was lifted in January 2009 by the Bombay High Court.<ref name=\"desh2\">{{Cite news |url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/latest-news/deshdrohi-ban-lifted/408977/ |title=Deshdrohi ban lifted |date=10 January 2009 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130807084359/http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/latest-news/deshdrohi-ban-lifted/408977/ |archive-date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Nagaland ===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]'': It was banned for portraying Jesus Christ and Christians in an 'objectionable' manner.<ref name=\"nagalandVinci\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/may/24da.htm |title=Nagaland bans Da Vinci Code |date=24 March 2006 |work=Rediff.com |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233808/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/may/24da.htm |archive-date=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Punjab ===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]'': Chief Minister [[Amarinder Singh]] banned the film after an appeal by the Punjabi Roman Catholic leaders.<ref name=\"punjabVinci\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5017498.stm |title=India's northern Punjab state has banned the screening of the new Hollywood film The Da Vinci Code. |date=25 May 2006 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102014310/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5017498.stm |archive-date=2 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Aarakshan]]'': On 11 August 2011, the film was banned for hurting the feelings of the weaker sections of the society.<ref name=\"punjabAar\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article2346568.ece |title=Punjab bans \u2018Aarakshan' |date=11 August 2011 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref> But, the ban was lifted on 14 August 2011 after a preview screening.<ref name=\"PunjabLiftsBan\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Punjab-lifts-ban-on-Aarakshan/Article1-733307.aspx |title=Punjab lifts ban on Aarakshan |date=14 August 2011 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402115821/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Punjab-lifts-ban-on-Aarakshan/Article1-733307.aspx |archive-date=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 ''[[Sadda Haq (film)|Sadda Haq]]'': On 4 April, [[Punjabi cinema|Punjabi film]] [[Sadda Haq (film)|Sadda Haq]] was banned in Punjab by the state government.<ref name=\"SaddaHaqBan\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/punjab-government-bans-controversial-film-sadda-haq-india-today/1/260747.html |title=Sadda Haq banned by Punjab government |date=5 April 2013 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=9 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109073502/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/punjab-government-bans-controversial-film-sadda-haq-india-today/1/260747.html |archive-date=9 January 2015}}</ref> The ban was lifted by the Supreme Court on 28 April 2013, after a special screening in the court.<ref name=\"SCSaddaHaq\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/movies/news/SC-lifts-ban-on-Sadda-Haq/articleshow/19755210.cms |title=SC lifts ban on Sadda Haq |date=28 April 2013 |work=[[The Times of India]]}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 ''Oh My Pyo Ji'': The [[Punjab and Haryana High Court]] stayed the release of the on the request of a producer due the dispute between two producers.\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[MSG: The Messenger]]'': The Punjab government banned [[Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh]]'s film [[MSG: The Messenger]] in the state.<ref name=\"MSG-IE\">{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/messenger-of-god-controversy-tension-in-pockets-of-sirsa-section-144-imposed-at-places/ |title=Ram Rahim Singh\u2019s \u2018Messenger of God\u2019 screening banned in Punjab, section 144 imposed in Sirsa after protest |date=20 January 2015 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |access-date=11 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160210094239/htt