rnment-suspends-screening-of-controversial-film-nanak-shah-fakir/article1-1337464.aspx |archive-date=11 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fakir-BS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/chandigarh-administration-bans-nanak-shah-fakir-115041700568_1.html |title=Chandigarh administration bans 'Nanak Shah Fakir' |date=17 April 2015 |website=[[Business Standard]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205034126/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/chandigarh-administration-bans-nanak-shah-fakir-115041700568_1.html |archive-date=5 December 2015 |access-date=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 ''[[MSG-2 The Messenger]]'': On the release day, the film was banned by [[Mansa, Punjab|Mansa administration]] in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] but ban was lifted later.<ref name=\"MSG2-TOI\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/MSG-2-On-day-Mansa-removes-ban-DC-says-didnt-know-about-it/articleshow/49006865.cms |title='MSG-2': On day Mansa removes ban, DC says didn't know about it |last=Amaninder Sharma |date=18 September 2015 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=19 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921035125/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/MSG-2-On-day-Mansa-removes-ban-DC-says-didnt-know-about-it/articleshow/49006865.cms |archive-date=21 September 2015}}</ref> However, movie theatres owners refused to screen movie in Punjab citing law and order problems.<ref name=\"Miss-HT\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/punjab-theatre-owners-give-gurmeet-ram-rahim-starrer--msg-2-a-miss/article1-1391320.aspx |title=Punjab theatre owners give MSG-2 a miss |date=18 September 2015 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=11 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923114251/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/punjab-theatre-owners-give-gurmeet-ram-rahim-starrer--msg-2-a-miss/article1-1391320.aspx |archive-date=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MSG2NoShow-TOI\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/The-Messenger-Pictures-from-its-grand-premiere/photostory/49023159.cms |title=No show of MSG-2 in Punjab, dera followers hold protest |date=19 September 2015 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=19 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920225725/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/The-Messenger-Pictures-from-its-grand-premiere/photostory/49023159.cms |archive-date=20 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Ruckus-Jag\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.jagran.com/punjab/moga-ruckus-in-punjab-on-ban-to-film-msg-2-stoped-rail-12908634.html |title=Ruckus in Punjab on ban to film MSG 2, rail traffic stopped |date=19 September 2015 |work=Jagran |access-date=19 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906180745/http://www.jagran.com/punjab/moga-ruckus-in-punjab-on-ban-to-film-msg-2-stoped-rail-12908634.html |archive-date=6 September 2017 |language=hi}}</ref>\n* 2016 \u2013 ''[[Santa Banta Pvt Ltd]]'': The film was banned by the state government for portraying [[Sikh]]s in a denigrating and defamatory manner.<ref name=\"Santa-NDTV\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/punjab-bans-santa-banta-pvt-ltd-for-allegedly-mocking-sikhs-1398749 |title=Punjab Bans Santa Banta Pvt Ltd For Allegedly Mocking Sikhs |date=13 April 2016 |work=[[NDTV]] |access-date=23 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424202926/http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/punjab-bans-santa-banta-pvt-ltd-for-allegedly-mocking-sikhs-1398749 |archive-date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Rajasthan ===\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Jodhaa Akbar]]'': The film was not released after theatre owners received letters written in blood from [[Shri Rajput Karni Sena|Karni Sena]].<ref name=\"Raj1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/feb/15ban.htm |title=Jodhaa Akbar not released in Rajasthan |date=15 February 2008 |work=Rediff.com |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123222146/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/feb/15ban.htm |archive-date=23 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Raj2\">{{Cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/gowariker-s-magnum-opus-jodhaa-akbar-releases-amid-controversy_424509.html |title=Gowariker's magnum opus Jodhaa Akbar releases amid controversy |date=15 February 2008 |work=Zee News |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 ''[[Padmaavat]]'': Following controversies and threats of violence made by Rajput caste organization ''Shri Rajput Karni Sena''.<ref name=\"Padmaavat ban 2017\" />\n\n=== Tamil Nadu ===\n* 1987 \u2013 ''[[Ore Oru Gramathiley]]'': It banned for criticizing [[Reservation in India|caste based reservations]]. The [[Supreme Court of India]] later allowed its release.<ref name=\"oreoru\">{{Cite web |url=http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/from-tollywood-a-landmark-case-on-free-speech/ |title=From Tamil Film, a Landmark Case on Free Speech |last=Subramanian |first=Samanth |website=India Ink (India blog of [[New York Times]]) |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530202802/http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/from-tollywood-a-landmark-case-on-free-speech/ |archive-date=30 May 2013 |access-date=7 May 2013}}</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]'': It was banned after concerns that it may hurt religious sentiments.<ref name=\"VinciBan\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dmk-govt-bans-the-da-vinci-code-/5538/ |title=DMK govt bans The Da Vinci Code |date=31 May 2006 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref> Later, Madras High Court allowed its screening.<ref name=\"VinciHC\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2006/jul/08tn.htm |title=Da Vinci Code to hit TN theatres, finally |date=8 July 2006 |work=Rediff.com |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225819/http://www.rediff.com/news/2006/jul/08tn.htm |archive-date=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Dam 999]]'': It was banned for allegedly spreading fear among people regarding the [[Mullaperiyar Dam]].<ref name=\"Dam999\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-24/chennai/30437083_1_new-dam-mullaperiyar-dam-tamil-nadu |title=Tamil Nadu govt bans screening of movie 'Dam 999' |last=R. Satyanarayana |date=24 November 2011 |work=The Times of India |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 ''[[Vishwaroopam]]'': The film was banned after objections were expressed by Muslim groups regarding the portrayal of the Muslim community in a bad light.<ref name=\"VishMuslim\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/muslim-groups-want-screening-of-viswaroopam-to-them-prior-to-release/1054083/0 |title=Muslim groups want screening of 'Viswaroopam' to them prior to release |date=3 January 2013 |work=Indian Express |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210095854/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/muslim-groups-want-screening-of-viswaroopam-to-them-prior-to-release/1054083/0 |archive-date=10 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"VishBan\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/Chennai/Vishwaroopam-ban-emotional-Kamal-Haasan-threatens-to-move-out-to-a-secular-land/Article1-1003738.aspx |title=Vishwaroopam ban: emotional Kamal Haasan threatens to move out to a 'secular' land |date=30 January 2013 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306064851/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/Chennai/Vishwaroopam-ban-emotional-Kamal-Haasan-threatens-to-move-out-to-a-secular-land/Article1-1003738.aspx |archive-date=6 March 2013}}</ref> The movie was later released after seven scenes were cut.<ref name=\"VishRelease\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/south/kamal-haasan-s-vishwaroopam-releases-in-tamil-nadu-finally-327550 |title=Kamal Haasan's Vishwaroopam releases in Tamil Nadu, finally |last=Malik |first=Surabhi |date=7 February 2013 |work=NDTV |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320085438/http://www.ndtv.com/article/south/kamal-haasan-s-vishwaroopam-releases-in-tamil-nadu-finally-327550 |archive-date=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 ''[[Madras Cafe]]'': The film, which is set in the backdrop of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]], was not released in the state after several groups protested that the film portrayed the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|Tamil Tigers]] in a bad light.<ref name=\"madras_cafe\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-23776412 |title=Madras Cafe: Bollywood film stirs up a storm in India |date=23 August 2013 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=16 February 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824150105/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-23776412 |archive-date=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 ''[[Inam \u2013 Ceylon]]'': The film, which is set in the backdrop of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]], was not released in the state after several groups protested that the film portrayed the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|Tamil Tigers]] in a bad light.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n=== Uttar Pradesh ===\n* 2007 \u2013 ''[[Aaja Nachle]]'' : The movie was banned because the lyrics of the title song was allegedly humiliating the [[Dalit]]s. The lyrics were later changed.<ref name=\"UPaaja\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/bollywood/20071201-2.html |title='Aaja Nachle' banned in UP and Punjab |date=1 December 2007 |work=ApunKaChoice.com |access-date=5 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002191024/http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/bollywood/20071201-2.html |archive-date=2 October 2015}}</ref> The ban was lifted later after the producers apologized.<ref name=\"UPaaja1\">{{Cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2007/12/01/idINIndia-30783120071201 |title=Uttar Pradesh lifts ban on \"Aaja Nachle\" |date=1 December 2007 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=5 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722100954/http://in.reuters.com/article/2007/12/01/idINIndia-30783120071201 |archive-date=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n* 2008 \u2013 ''[[Jodhaa Akbar]]'' : The film was banned fearing breach of peace after protests from a Rajput group.<ref name=\"JodhaaRajput\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-03-01/india/27766847_1_bans-screening-rajput |title=UP bans screening of Jodhaa Akbar |date=1 March 2008 |work=The Times of India |access-date=7 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UPJodhaa\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/jodhaa-akbar-banned-in-uttar-pradesh-news-bollywood-kkftO8dhdhe.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130807084314/http://www.sify.com/movies/jodhaa-akbar-banned-in-uttar-pradesh-news-bollywood-kkftO8dhdhe.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 August 2013 |title=Jodhaa Akbar banned in Uttar Pradesh |date=2 March 2008 |work=Sify.com |access-date=4 August 2013 }}</ref> The Supreme Court later lifted the ban.<ref name=\"SCJodhaa\" />\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Aarakshan]]'' : It had been banned due to objectionable dialogues.<ref name=\"UPAar\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-08-11/lucknow/29875976_1_aarakshan-bans-screening |title=UP govt bans release of 'Aarakshan' |date=11 August 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref> Later, Supreme Court lifted the ban.<ref name=\"SCAarUp\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article2372834.ece |title=Suspension of Aarakshan screening in U.P. quashed |date=19 August 2011 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110909015022/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article2372834.ece |archive-date=9 September 2011}}</ref> The film was based on the topic of [[Reservation in India|reservations]] in jobs and education.\n\n=== West Bengal ===\n* 1992 \u2013 ''[[City of Joy (film)|City of Joy]]'' : The shooting was banned in Calcutta for a while due to negative portrayal of the city.<ref name=\"city of joy\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/23/movies/city-of-joy-starts-filming-but-calcutta-still-simmers.html |title=City of Protests : India: The filming of 'City of Joy' has brought Hollywood to Calcutta and raised charges that the movie is 'social pornography.' |last=Fineman |first=Mark |date=28 March 1991 |work=LA Times |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525232242/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/23/movies/city-of-joy-starts-filming-but-calcutta-still-simmers.html |archive-date=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 ''[[Kangal Malsat]]'' : In February 2013, a revising committee of the CBFC refused to pass the film citing excessive use of abusive language, sexuality and frivolous approach in portraying of social movements. The film was cleared later by the Film Certification Appellate Tribunal after some edits.<ref name=\"kangal1\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/mamata-banerjee-film-kangal-malsa-gets-red-signal-trinamool-congress-government/1/251565.html |title=Film critical of Mamata Banerjee gets red-signal |date=24 February 2013 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=7 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607091038/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/mamata-banerjee-film-kangal-malsa-gets-red-signal-trinamool-congress-government/1/251565.html |archive-date=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Stalin\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130225/jsp/calcutta/story_16601307.jsp#.UTBnVjeElZM |title=Censors cite Stalin & CM! |last=Das |first=Mohua |date=25 February 2013 |work=The Telegraph Calcutta |access-date=1 March 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228162415/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130225/jsp/calcutta/story_16601307.jsp#.UTBnVjeElZM |archive-date=28 February 2013 |location=Calcutta, India}}</ref><ref name=\"Top 10 Hindi\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PKDlNjdzU2M |title=Top 10 Banned Movies in India! |last=Youtube India |first=Top 10 Hindi |date=25 November 2017 |location=mumbai, India}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Censorship in India]]\n*[[Cinema of India]]\n*[[List of books banned in India]]\n*[[List of banned films]]\n*[[Film censorship]]\n*[[Moral police]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Banned films by country}}\n\n[[Category:Film censorship in India]]\n[[Category:Lists of banned films|India]]\n[[Category:Indian film-related lists|Banned]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in film| List India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2017}}\nThis is a '''list of [[film]]s that have been or are banned in [[India]]'''. This list includes titles that were refused a rating by the [[Central Board of Film Certification]] (CBFC) initially or permanently. The list also includes films whose release or production was or are blocked by the central or a state government, or by a legal institution. Also included are films which faced a virtual ban, after theatre owners were compelled to stop screening by non-government groups.\n{{Expand list|date=August 2013}}\n\n== Nationwide ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Film\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Neel Akasher Neechey]]''\n| It was banned for two months for overt political overtones; it showed the troubles faced by an immigrant Chinese wage laborer in 1930s Calcutta.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/Culture/Cinema/Mrinal.html |title=Mrinal Sen |publisher=sscnet |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208031623/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/Culture/Cinema/Mrinal.html |archive-date=8 February 2012 |access-date=2010-02-23}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''Gokul Shankar''\n| It was banned for depicting the psychological motivations of [[Nathuram Godse]], the assassin of [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref name=\"Roger2004\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tUAVk84xBGUC&pg=PR10 |title=Charisma and Commitment in South Asian History: Essays Presented to Stanley Wolpert |last=Roger D. Long |publisher=Orient Blackswan |year=2004 |isbn=978-81-250-2641-9 |page=10 |access-date=6 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1973\n|''[[Garam Hawa]]''\n| The release was held up by the censors for 8 months. The film depicted a Muslim family during the [[partition of India]].<ref name=\"Daiya2011\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P7a-FuiMcTYC&pg=PA138 |title=Violent Belongings: Partition, Gender, and National Culture in Postcolonial India |last=Kavita Daiya |date=4 February 2011 |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=978-1-59213-744-2 |page=138 |access-date=6 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627193046/http://books.google.com/books?id=P7a-FuiMcTYC&pg=PA138 |archive-date=27 June 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Aandhi]]''\n| It was banned during [[The Emergency (India)|Emergency]] by [[Indira Gandhi]] and subsequently released in 1977 after [[Janata Party]] came into power.<ref name=\"yahoo-ref\">{{Cite web |url=http://in.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/24fps/controversial-films-061836779.html?page=all |title=Ten most controversial films |last=Sinha |first=Sayoni |publisher=[[Yahoo]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209223544/http://in.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/24fps/controversial-films-061836779.html?page=all |archive-date=9 February 2013 |access-date=7 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Kissa Kursi Ka]]''\n| A political spoof, the film was banned by the [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] government for lampooning the [[The Emergency (India)|Emergency]].<ref name=\"Kissa1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/ban-culture-goes-back-a-long-way/article4373077.ece |title=Ban culture goes back a long way |date=3 February 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=5 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601031820/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/ban-culture-goes-back-a-long-way/article4373077.ece |archive-date=1 June 2013}}</ref> The master prints and all copies was lifted from the Censor Board office and burned by [[Sanjay Gandhi]] supporters.<ref name=\"Kissa2\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/1978-+Kissa+Kursi+Ka:+Celluloid+chutzpah/1/76362.html |title=1978- Kissa Kursi Ka: Celluloid chutzpah |date=28 December 2009 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=5 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603011739/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/1978-+Kissa+Kursi+Ka:+Celluloid+chutzpah/1/76362.html |archive-date=3 June 2013}}</ref> The movie was later remade with a different cast.\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Sikkim (film)|Sikkim]]''\n| The film was banned after Sikkim's merger in India in 1975, as it showed the [[Chogyal]]-ruled Sikkim as a sovereign state. The ban was lifted in September 2010.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11345987 |title=Ban on Satyajit Ray film lifted |date=17 September 2010 |access-date=20 June 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202064651/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11345987 |archive-date=2 December 2017 |publisher=BBC News, Calcutta}}</ref>\n\n|- 1979 '''Khak aur Khoon'''  [Urdu Film] [[Pakistan]]\n     {{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n| 1984\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''\n| It was banned temporarily for its \"negative\" depiction of Indians because of a scene, set in India, where characters are served monkey brains. Monkeys are seen as sacred animals in Hinduism. The ban was later rescinded.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://images.businessweek.com/ss/06/11/1106_banned/source/7.htm |title=Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom |date=1 April 2007 |website=BusinessWeek |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401050227/http://images.businessweek.com/ss/06/11/1106_banned/source/7.htm |archive-date=1 April 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''Pati Parmeshwar''\n| It was denied a rating by the Censor for depicting a woman in \"ignoble servility\" of her husband. Later, Bombay High Court allowed its release.<ref name=\"Gangoli2007\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SKkzbVsmGOQC&pg=PA77 |title=Indian Feminisms: Law, Patriarchies and Violence in India |last=Geetanjali Gangoli |date=1 January 2007 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |isbn=978-1-4094-9074-6 |page=77 |access-date=7 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mitter1991\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CeeIimZ7LxAC&pg=PA66 |title=Dharma's Daughters: Contemporary Indian Women and Hindu Culture |last=Sara S. Mitter |publisher=Rutgers University Press |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-8135-1678-3 |page=66 |access-date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|1993\n| ''[[Kuttrapathirikai]]''\n|The film was completed in 1993. As it had [[Rajiv Gandhi]]'s<ref name=\"Rajiv1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/11/21/stories/2006112105420500.htm |title=High Court judges to see `Kutrapathirikkai' |date=21 November 2006 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004222750/http://www.hindu.com/2006/11/21/stories/2006112105420500.htm |archive-date=4 October 2008}}</ref>  assassination as a backdrop, it was not released until 2007.\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Bandit Queen]]''\n| It was banned temporarily by the [[Delhi High Court]] after [[Phoolan Devi]], the subject of the film's story, challenged its authenticity.<ref name=\"Roy2010\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RKuohALLNgsC&pg=PA75 |title=Outlaw: India's Bandit Queen and Me |last=Roy Moxham |date=3 June 2010 |publisher=Ebury Publishing |isbn=978-1-4070-8013-0 |page=75 |access-date=6 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Kama Sutra: A Tale of Love]]''\n| It was banned due to sexual content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/clamping-down-on-creativity/article17739798.ece |title=Clamping down on creativity |last=Chauhan |first=R. s |date=30 March 2017 |via=www.thehindu.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206082912/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/clamping-down-on-creativity/article17739798.ece |archive-date=6 February 2018 |access-date=10 October 2017}}</ref> The version released in India had 2 minute cut of nudity.\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Fire (1996 film)|Fire]]''\n| On its opening day in India, some film theatres were attacked by Hindu fundamentalists for depicting a [[lesbian]] relationship.<ref name=\"BBCFireAttacked\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/227273.stm |title=Hindu militants stage lesbian film attacks |date=3 December 1998 |work=BBC News |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140130192008/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/227273.stm |archive-date=30 January 2014}}</ref>  The film was withdrawn and sent back to the [[Central Board of Film Certification|Censor Board]].<ref name=\"BBCWithdrawFire\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/229320.stm |title=Film star slams lesbian movie withdrawal |date=7 December 1998 |work=BBC News |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140130192013/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/229320.stm |archive-date=30 January 2014}}</ref> But, later it was released uncut.<ref name=\"BCCFireUncut\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/279351.stm |title=India approves lesbian film |date=14 February 1999 |work=BBC News |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129063726/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/279351.stm |archive-date=29 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Paanch]]''\n| It was banned for glorifying drugs, sex and violence, later certified with cuts but went unreleased.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?213038 |title=Rock 'N' Roll Banned |last=Joshi |first=Namrata |date=3 September 2001 |work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |access-date=7 May 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305110250/http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?213038 |archive-date=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Hawayein]]''\n| The film, set against the backdrop to the [[1984 anti-Sikh riots|1984 Sikh genocide]], is banned in the Indian states of Delhi, J&K, Haryana and Punjab.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/03/sep/03hawayein.asp |title=Hawayein faces government hurdles |access-date=9 July 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714154945/http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/03/sep/03hawayein.asp |archive-date=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Pink Mirror]]''\n| The film was denied a rating for its homosexual content.<ref name=\"pink1\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3689509.stm |title=UK premiere for Indian drag film |last=Smith |first=Neil |date=6 May 2004 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=7 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210120/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3689509.stm |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Final Solution (2003 film)|Final Solution]]''\n| The documentary film was banned by the [[Central Board of Film Certification|Censor Board]] for being provocative and under concerns that it may trigger communal violence.<ref name=\"FinalSolution\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3542340.stm |title=India bans religious riot movie |date=6 August 2004 |work=BBC News |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920234437/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3542340.stm |archive-date=20 September 2013}}</ref>  It was based on the [[2002 Gujarat violence]]. But, it was cleared after some months.<ref name=\"FinalSolution2\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-10-15/india/27152434_1_anupam-kher-i-b-ministry-documentary-on-gujarat-riots |title=Kher didn't block 'Final Solution', he helped pass it |date=11 October 2004 |work=The Times of India |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Hava Aney Dey]]''\n| The movie was not approved by the [[Central Board of Film Certification|Censor Board]] because the director didn't accept the suggested 21 cuts.<ref name=\"Hava\">{{Cite web |url=http://dearcinema.com/article/hava-aney-dey-a-chance-lost-to-censor/5143 |title=Hava Aney Dey: a chance lost to censor |last=Dutta |first=Nandita |publisher=Dear Cinema |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915233753/http://dearcinema.com/article/hava-aney-dey-a-chance-lost-to-censor/5143 |archive-date=15 September 2013 |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Black Friday (2004 film)]]''\n| The movie was based on the [[1993 Bombay bombings]]. The released was blocked until the verdict of the lawsuit by the [[Bombay High Court]] on the petition of the under-trials.<ref name=\"Black2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/14330.html |title=High court stay on 'Black Friday' upheld |date=21 April 2005 |work=IndiaGlitz |access-date=6 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022134309/http://indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/14330.html |archive-date=22 October 2007}}</ref>  The film was originally set to be released in India on 28 January 2005.<ref name=\"Black1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/producers-of-black-friday-move-supreme-court-news-bollywood-kkfv91ajiia.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130807084336/http://www.sify.com/movies/producers-of-black-friday-move-supreme-court-news-bollywood-kkfv91ajiia.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 August 2013 |title=Producers of 'Black Friday' move Supreme Court |date=28 January 2005 |work=Sify.com |access-date=5 August 2013 }}</ref> The producers appealed at the Supreme Court but the High Court order was upheld. The movie finally saw its release on 9 February 2007.<ref name=\"BlackRelease\">{{Cite news |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/black-friday-hits-theatres-today/top/32181-8.html |title=Finally, Black Friday gets go ahead |date=18 June 2007 |work=IBNLive |access-date=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Amu (film)|Amu]]''\n| This movie was based on the [[1984 anti-Sikh riots]] initially was denied a rating. The film was later given an adult rating after some audio-cuts.<ref name=\"Amu1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2005/jan/10amu.htm |title=If Fahrenheit 9/11 can, so can Amu |date=10 January 2005 |work=[[Rediff]] |access-date=5 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916205748/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2005/jan/10amu.htm |archive-date=16 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Amu2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2204/stories/20050225001608900.htm |title=The horrors of the anti-Sikh riots of 1984 are revisited in two recent feature films with pertinent questions about identities and memories. |date=25 February 2005 |work=[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]] |access-date=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ShonaliBose\">{{Cite news |url=http://bollyspice.com/5774/it-is-preposterous-that-our-films-should-be-censored-shonali-bose |title=\"It is preposterous that our films should be censored!\" \u2013 Shonali Bose |date=19 October 2008 |work=Bollyspice |access-date=5 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402091231/http://bollyspice.com/5774/it-is-preposterous-that-our-films-should-be-censored-shonali-bose |archive-date=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Water (2005 film)|Water]]''\n| The movie faced opposition during its shooting from hardline Hindu organizations in [[Varanasi]]. The sets were destroyed.<ref name=\"Water2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2000/02/01/stories/01010002.htm |title=Deepa Mehta to seek Centre's intervention |date=1 February 2000 |work=The Hindu |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref> The Uttar Pradesh government decided to stop the shooting on 31 January 2000.<ref name=\"Water1\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2000/jan/31up.htm |title=UP government decides not to allow shooting of Water |date=31 January 2000 |work=Rediff.com |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090251/http://www.rediff.com/news/2000/jan/31up.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref> The shooting was shifted to Sri Lanka later. The movie was released in India much later in March 2007.\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Had Anhad''\n| The Central Board of Film Certification refused a certificate to this [[Shabnam Virmani]] documentary without cuts. In 2011, Delhi High Court allowed the film to be released uncut and asked the Union of India to pay {{currency|10000|inr}} to the petitioner as legal fees.<ref name=\"kabir\">{{Cite news |url=https://in.movies.yahoo.com/news/court-paves-way-release-documentary-kabir-20110309-073902-100.html |title=Court paves way for release of documentary on Kabir |date=9 March 2011 |work=[[Yahoo.com]] |access-date=23 May 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524031458/https://in.movies.yahoo.com/news/court-paves-way-release-documentary-kabir-20110309-073902-100.html |archive-date=24 May 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Gandu (film)|Gandu]]\n|The film was banned in India due to explicit sexual scenes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/bollywood-welcomes-censor-boards-decision-to-withdraw-cuss-words-list-1203240 |title=Bollywood Welcomes Censor Boards Decision to Withdraw Cuss Words List \u2013 NDTV Movies |date=2015-08-03 |website=Movies.ndtv.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208210525/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/bollywood-welcomes-censor-boards-decision-to-withdraw-cuss-words-list-1203240 |archive-date=8 December 2015 |access-date=2016-01-11}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2011 film)|The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo]]''\n| It was banned for its adult scenes of rape and torture. The Central Board of Film Certification demanded that these scenes be cut, which the director [[David Fincher]] refused to do.<ref name=\"dragon tattoo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/29/idUS122486517520120129 |title=India Bans 'Girl With the Dragon Tattoo' |date=29 January 2012 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=27 February 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302235031/http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/29/idUS122486517520120129 |archive-date=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Chatrak]]\n|The movie wasn't allowed theatrical release due to its sexual content.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/13-indian-films-that-have-made-us-proud-and-wowed-audiences-at-international-film-festivals-232833.html |title=13 Indian Films That Have Made Us Proud At International Film Festivals! |website=indiatimes.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021210403/http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/13-indian-films-that-have-made-us-proud-and-wowed-audiences-at-international-film-festivals-232833.html |archive-date=21 October 2015 |access-date=2015-12-08}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Papilio Buddha (film)|Papilio Buddha]]\n| Initially banned due to its criticism of [[Mahatma Gandhi]]. It was allowed release after the anti-Gandhi speeches were muted and/or blurred.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://berlinfilmjournal.com/2014/09/controversial-cinema-top-10-banned-films/ |title=Controversial Cinema: Top 10 Banned Films |last=Beaney |first=Harriet |publisher=Berlin Film Journal |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125150859/http://berlinfilmjournal.com/2014/09/controversial-cinema-top-10-banned-films/ |archive-date=25 January 2016 |access-date=2016-01-11 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Gurjar Aandolan A Fight for Right (Movie)]]''\n| This film was banned by Rajasthan Government after the [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] (Rajasthan Government) watched this movie in Laxmi Talkies, Jaipur, on the day of its release on 17 October 2014. This film was based on Gurjar Agitation held in Rajasthan by Gurjar cast in 2007, and 2008 by the Gurjar Leader Colonel Kirori Mal Bainsla. All the news papers and media declared this news of banned on this movie on 17 and 18 October 2014.\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[No Fire Zone]]''\n| The [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] documentary was not allowed for public screening by the Censor Board. Director [[Callum Macrae]] decided to release the film on the internet to circumvent the ban.<ref name=\"no_fire_zone\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/worldcinema/film-on-sri-lankan-war-banned-in-india/article1-1187291.aspx |title=Film on Sri Lankan war banned in India |date=23 February 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=27 February 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223214811/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/worldcinema/film-on-sri-lankan-war-banned-in-india/article1-1187291.aspx |archive-date=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Kaum De Heere]]''\n| The film was banned by the central government after the [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] had warned that the film may cause communal tensions. The film glorified the assassins of former Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]].<ref name=\"KaumDeHeere\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Centre-blocks-release-of-controversial-film-on-Indira-Gandhis-assassins-Kaum-de-Heere/articleshow/40606687.cms |title=Centre blocks release of controversial film on Indira Gandhi\u2019s assassins \u2018Kaum de Heere\u2019 |date=21 August 2014 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=8 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121153206/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Centre-blocks-release-of-controversial-film-on-Indira-Gandhis-assassins-Kaum-de-Heere/articleshow/40606687.cms |archive-date=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''\n| The film was not given a rating by the Censor Board, even after voluntary cuts by the distributor.<ref name=\"ShadesofGrey\">{{Cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2015/03/04/film-fiftyshades-india-idINKBN0M01TV20150304?irpc=932 |title=India's censor blocks 'Fifty Shades of Grey' from cinemas |date=4 March 2015 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=5 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307142348/http://in.reuters.com/article/2015/03/04/film-fiftyshades-india-idINKBN0M01TV20150304?irpc=932 |archive-date=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Main Hoon Rajinikanth]]''\n| Notable south Indian actor [[Rajinikanth]] moved the Madras High Court to stop the release of this film stating that it violated his [[personality rights]]. A stay was granted, and the makers of the movie were directed not use superstar's name, image or likeness.<ref name=\"Rajni\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Superstar-Rajinikanth-moves-Madras-high-court-to-stop-release-of-Bollywood-movie-named-after-him/articleshow/42702543.cms |title=Superstar Rajinikanth moves Madras high court to stop release of Bollywood movie named after him |date=17 September 2014 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=6 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927213222/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Superstar-Rajinikanth-moves-Madras-high-court-to-stop-release-of-Bollywood-movie-named-after-him/articleshow/42702543.cms |archive-date=27 September 2014}}</ref> The director [[Faisal Saif]] later said he had shown the film to the actor and his lawyers to assure them. The film's title was later changed to ''Main Hoon (Part-Time) Killer''.<ref name=\"NameChangeRajni\">{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/faisal-saif-changes-title-of-main-hoon-rajinikanth-film/ |title=Faisal Saif changes title of \u2018Main Hoon Rajinikanth\u2019 film |date=14 October 2014 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |access-date=6 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108194124/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/faisal-saif-changes-title-of-main-hoon-rajinikanth-film/ |archive-date=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Unfreedom]]''\n| The film was denied a rating by the Censor Board. The film examined same sex relationships and religious fundamentalism in India. The director [[Raj Amit Kumar]] was told by the Board that film will cause clashes between Hindus and Muslims, and will provoke \"unnatural passions\".<ref name=\"Unfreedom\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.americanbazaaronline.com/2015/02/11/banned-india-unfreedom-raj-amit-kumar-released-us-theaters/ |title=Banned in India, \u2018Unfreedom\u2019 by Raj Amit Kumar to be released in US theaters |date=11 February 2015 |work=The American Bazaar |access-date=28 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402125138/http://www.americanbazaaronline.com/2015/02/11/banned-india-unfreedom-raj-amit-kumar-released-us-theaters/ |archive-date=2 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"IgniteUnnatural\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/entertainment/