==\n\n=== Provinces of British India ===\n* 1921 \u2013 ''[[Bhakta Vidur]]'': Banned in Karachi and [[Madras Presidency|Madras]] for political reasons.<ref name=\"Woods2011\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jw-2w-SpuZMC&pg=PA98 |title=Visions of Empire and Other Imaginings: Cinema, Ireland and India 1910\u20131962 |last=Jeannine Woods |publisher=Peter Lang |year=2011 |isbn=978-3-03911-974-5 |page=98 |access-date=17 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004728/http://books.google.com/books?id=Jw-2w-SpuZMC&pg=PA98 |archive-date=2 May 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> the film came right after [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]] and [[Rowlatt Act]]. The character [[Vidura]] was moulded upon personality of [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref name=\"Dwyer2006\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8qjKJ0yk-gQC&pg=PA72 |title=Filming the Gods: Religion and Indian Cinema |last=Rachel Dwyer |date=30 August 2006 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-203-08865-4 |pages=72\u2013 |access-date=18 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002325/http://books.google.com/books?id=8qjKJ0yk-gQC&pg=PA72 |archive-date=2 May 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 1939 \u2013 ''[[Thyagabhoomi]]'': Banned in [[Madras Presidency|Madras]], 22 weeks after release for supporting [[Indian National Congress|Congress]], [[Indian independence movement|independence movement]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2008/03/21/stories/2008032150321600.htm |title=Blast from the past |last=Guy |first=Randor |date=2008-03-21 |work=The Hindu |access-date=2013-07-26 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108170427/http://www.hindu.com/cp/2008/03/21/stories/2008032150321600.htm |archive-date=8 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Andhra Pradesh ===\n* 2006 \u2013 ''[[The Da Vinci Code (film)|The Da Vinci Code]]'': It was banned after some Christians and Muslims who took offence protested.<ref name=\"VinciAndhra\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/06/02/stories/2006060207640600.htm |title=`The Da Vinci Code' banned in Andhra Pradesh |date=2 June 2006 |work=The Hindu |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422204751/http://www.hindu.com/2006/06/02/stories/2006060207640600.htm |archive-date=22 April 2008}}</ref> Later, the ban was lifted by the [[High Court of Judicature at Hyderabad|Andhra Pradesh High Court]].<ref name=\"VinciAndhraHC\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-22/hyderabad/27794062_1_quashes-film-expert-body |title=HC quashes ban on Da Vinci Code |date=22 June 2006 |work=The Times of India |access-date=4 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225165605/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-06-22/hyderabad/27794062_1_quashes-film-expert-body |archive-date=25 December 2013}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 ''[[Aarakshan]]'': It was banned on 11 August 2011 due to concerns that it may hurt weaker sections of the society.<ref name=\"APAar\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1574946/report-now-andhra-pradesh-bans-aarakshan |title=Now, Andhra Pradesh bans Aarakshan |date=11 August 2011 |work=[[DNA India]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref> On 14 August 2011, the ban was revoked.<ref name=\"APAar2\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-08-14/india/29886448_1_aarakshan-ban-statewide-ban-prakash-jha-s-aarakshan |title=AP, Punjab lift Aarakshan ban |date=14 August 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=4 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Assam ===\n* 1952 \u2013 ''[[Runumi]]'': The film was suddenly banned by then [[Government of Assam]] headed by chief minister [[Bishnuram Medhi]] due to some unknown reason.<ref name=\"ab\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.assamtribune.com/scripts/detailsnew.asp?id=mar1510/at09 |title=Lost treasure of Assamese cinema retrieved |last=Staff Reporter |date=14 March 2010 |publisher=The Assam Tribune |url-status