 |publisher=Williams and Norgate |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxSDvgAACAAJ |language=en |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Mathiez |first=Albert |date=1977 |title=Robespierre: l'histoire et la l\u00e9gende |jstor=41915887 |journal=Annales Historiques de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise |volume=49 |issue=227 |pages=5\u201331 |ref=harv|doi=10.3406/ahrf.1977.4029 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Mathiez |first1=Albert |title=Etudes sur Robespierre: 1758\u20131794 |date=1988 |publisher=Messidor |location=Paris |isbn=978-2209060498 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Matrat |first1=Jean |title=Robespierre: or, The tyranny of the majority |date=1975 |publisher=Scribner |location=New York |isbn=978-0684140551 |url=https://archive.org/details/robespierreortyr0000matr |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=McPhee |first1=Peter |title=Robespierre: A Revolutionary Life |date=2012 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0300118117 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kYLu7-cPJTYC |language=en |ref=harv}}\n* Michelet, Jules (1847) The History of the French Revolution (Charles Cocks, trans.) online\n* {{cite book |last=Moore |first=Lucy |title=Liberty: The Lives and Times of Six Women in Revolutionary France |url=https://archive.org/details/libertylivestime0000moor |url-access=registration |date=2007-05-08 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn=978-0-06-082526-3 |oclc=76836264 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Robespierre |first1=Charlotte |title=M\u00e9moires |date=2006 |publisher=Nouveau monde \u00e9d. |location=Paris |isbn=978-2847361766 |edition=Nouv. \u00e9d. |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Robespierre |first=Maximilien de |editor1-last=Bouloiseau |editor1-first=Marc |editor2-last=Lefebvre |editor2-first=Georges |editor3-last=Soboul |editor3-first=Albert |editor4-last=Dautry |editor4-first=Jean |title=Oeuvres de Maximilien Robespierre |date=1958 |publisher=PUF |language=French |oclc=370022395 |url=https://archive.org/details/oeuvrescomplte09robeuoft |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Rud\u00e9 |first1=George F.E. |title=Robespierre: portrait of a Revolutionary Democrat |date=1975 |publisher=Collins |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xDAJAQAAIAAJ |language=en |ref=harv}} A political portrait of Robespierre, examining his changing image among historians and the different aspects of Robespierre as an 'ideologue', as a political democrat, as a social democrat, as a practitioner of revolution, as a politician and as a popular leader/leader of revolution. It also touches on his legacy to future revolutionary leaders [[Vladimir Lenin]] and [[Mao Zedong]].\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Simon Schama |last=Schama |first=Simon |title=Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |year=1989 |isbn=978-0-394-55948-3 |title-link=Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Scurr |first1=Ruth |title=Fatal Purity: Robespierre and the French Revolution |date=2006 |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York |isbn=978-0805082616 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CojtKDmS_ocC&dq=Fatal+Purity+2006 |language=en |ref=harv}}\n** {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609051033/http://www.lrb.co.uk/v28/n08/print/mant01_.html |date=9 June 2007 |title=Reviewed}} by Hilary Mantel in the ''London Review of Books'', Vol. 28 No. 8, 20 April 2006.\n** [http://www.the-tls.co.uk/tls/reviews/history/article759667.ece Reviewed] by Sudhir Hazareesingh in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', 7 June 2006.\n* Sanson, Henri (1876). Memoirs of the Sansons: From Private Notes and Documents (1688-1847). London: Chatto and Windus. OCLC 317736774\n* {{cite book |last1=Soboul |first1=Albert |title=Dictionnaire historique de la R\u00e9volution fran\u00e7aise |date=2005 |publisher=Quadrige / PUF |location=Paris |isbn=978-2130536055 |edition=1. \u00e9d. |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Soboul |first1=Albert |title=The French Revolution, 1787\u20131799: from the storming of the Bastille to Napoleon |date=1974 |publisher=Vintage Books |isbn=978-0394712208 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2gt4AAAAIAAJ |language=en |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=J.M. |title=Robespierre |date=1988 |publisher=B. Blackwell |location=New York |isbn=978-0631155041 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Popkin |first1=Jeremy D. |title=You Are All Free: The Haitian Revolution and the Abolition of Slavery |date=2010 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521517225 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U8IHym0hoQwC |language=en |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\nAccording to David P. Jordan: \"Any comprehensive bibliography would be virtually impossible. In 1936 G\u00e9rard Walter drew up a list of over 10,000 works on Robespierre, and much has been done since.\"<!--<ref>[Jordan, David P. \"Robespierre.\" The Journal of Modern History, vol. 49, no. 2, 1977, pp. 282\u2013291. {{JSTOR|1876343}}</ref>-->\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n* [[Richard Cobb]], ''Les arm\u00e9es r\u00e9volutionnaires. Instrument de la Terreur dans les d\u00e9partements. Avril 1793-Flor\u00e9al An II'', Paris-La Haye, Mouton and C\u00b0, 1961\u20131963, 2 volumes in-8\u00b0, VIII\u20131017, [http://www.persee.fr/doc/bec_0373-6237_1965_num_123_1_449698_t1_0273_0000_3 pr\u00e9sentation en ligne], [http://www.persee.fr/doc/ahess_0395-2649_1966_num_21_1_421363_t1_0213_0000_2 pr\u00e9sentation en ligne].\n* Cobban, Alfred. \"The Political Ideas of Maximilien Robespierre during the Period of the Convention\", ''English Historical Review'' Vol. 61, No. 239 (January 1946), pp.&nbsp;45\u201380 {{JSTOR|554837}}\n* Cobban, Alfred. \"The Fundamental Ideas of Robespierre\", ''English Historical Review'' Vol. 63, No. 246 (January 1948), pp.&nbsp;29\u201351 {{JSTOR|555187}}\n* {{cite book |author=Eagan, James Michael |title=Maximilien Robespierre: Nationalist Dictator |location=New York |publisher=Octagon Books |year=1978 |isbn=978-0-374-92440-9}} Presents Robespierre as the origin of Fascist dictators.\n* [[Donald Clark Hodges|Hodges, Donald Clark]] (2003) ''Deep Republicanism: Prelude to Professionalism''. Lexington Books.\n* Linton, Marisa. \"Robespierre and the Terror\", ''History Today'', August 2006, Volume 56, Issue 8, pp.&nbsp;23\u201329 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313181009/http://www.historytoday.com/dt_main_allatonce.asp?gid=31771&aid=&tgid=&amid=30232604&g31771=x&g31763=x&g30026=x&g20991=x&g21010=x&g19965=x&g19963=x |date=13 March 2007 |title=online}}\n* Linton, Marisa, 'Robespierre et l'authenticit\u00e9 r\u00e9volutionnaire', ''Annales Historiques de la R\u00e9volution Fran\u00e7aise'', 371 (janvier-mars 2013): 153\u201373.\n* {{cite book |author=Palmer, R.R. |title=Twelve Who Ruled: The Year of Terror in the French Revolution |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=1941 |isbn=978-0-691-05119-2 |author-link=R.R. Palmer}} A sympathetic study of the [[Committee of Public Safety]].\n* {{cite book |last1=Robespierre |first1=Maximilien |last2=\u017di\u017eek |first2=Slavoj |editor1-last=Ducange |editor1-first=Jean |translator-last1=Howe |translator-first1=John |date=2017 |title=Virtue and Terror |url= |location= |publisher=Verso |series=Revolutions |page= |isbn=978-1786633378 |author-link2=Slavoj \u017di\u017eek}}\n* [[Albert Soboul|Soboul, Albert]]. \"Robespierre and the Popular Movement of 1793\u20134\", ''Past and Present'', No. 5. (May 1954), pp.&nbsp;54\u201370. {{JSTOR|649823}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Maximilien de Robespierre}}\n{{Wikisource|Author:Maximilien Robespierre}}\n{{Wikiquote|Maximilien Robespierre}}\n\n* [[La R\u00e9volution fran\u00e7aise (film)]] by [[Richard T. Heffron]] (1989 dramatisation reflecting the official narrative of the Bicentenary commemorations, for which it was made.): [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zNAd8QjBtlg The French Revolution \u2014 Part 2 \u2014 English subtitles]\n* [http://www.amis-robespierre.org/Biographie-elements-essentiels-de Biography: essential elements of his life]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3fBP7m2mNDM&t=1969s Conspiracy and Terror in the French Revolution \u2013 Marisa Linton (Kingston University) Public Lecture]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=occ7Sp1OpOk&t=1924s The Robespierre Problem \u2013 Peter McPhee (University of Melbourne) and Colin Jones (University of London) discussion]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FX03HWtOEa4&t=21s Le Grand M\u00e9chant Robespierre \u2013 Marc B\u00e9lissa and Yannick Bosc \u2013 discussion in French, dissecting the creation of the ''l\u00e9gende noire''] with subtitles\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N8QxxnHSpCI Herv\u00e9 Leuwers (University of Lille) on Robespierre (French)] with subtitles\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Maximilien Robespierre}}\n\n{{French Revolution navbox}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robespierre, Maximilien}}\n[[Category:Maximilien Robespierre| ]]\n[[Category:1758 births]]\n[[Category:1794 deaths]]\n[[Category:French revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Deputies to the French National Convention]]\n[[Category:Artesian people]]\n[[Category:French deists]]\n[[Category:French jurists]]\n[[Category:French republicans]]\n[[Category:Jacobins]]\n[[Category:French shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Leaders ousted by a coup]]\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand alumni]]\n[[Category:Montagnards]]\n[[Category:French people executed by guillotine during the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:People from Arras]]\n[[Category:Executed revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Regicides of Louis XVI]]\n[[Category:18th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Critics of the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:People on the Committee of Public Safety]]\n[[Category:People of the Reign of Terror]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the National Convention]]\n[[Category:Critics of atheism]]\n[[Category:18th-century French lawyers]]\n[[Category:Anti-monarchists]]\n[[Category:18th-century jurists]]\n", "name_user": "Taksen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy and memory:problematic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximilien_Robespierre"}
{"title_page": "Babbu Maan", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian singer-songwriter, actor and film producer}}\n{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Babbu Maan\n| image            = Babbu Maan Baarish Ke Bahaane (cropped).jpg\n| image_size       = 150px\n| caption          = Maan launching \"Baarish Ke Bahaane\"\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = <!-- Please do not add without a published reliable source. -->\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_place      = [[Khant Maanpur]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], India<ref name=\"birth\"/>\n| genre            = [[Folk music of Punjab|Folk]], [[Bhangra (popular music)|Bhangra]], Pop, [[Ghazal]]s\n| occupation       = Singer, lyricist, music director, actor, producer, screenwriter\n| years_active     = 1997\u2013present\n| label            = Catrack, [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]], Point Zero, [[Eros International]], Swag Music, Speed Records, [[Zee Music Company]], [[Sony Music India|Sony Music]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Jaspinder Narula]], [[Monty Sharma]], [[Jaidev Kumar]], [[Harjit Harman]], [[Harbhajan Mann]], [[Bhagwant Maan]], [[Gurdas Maan]], [[Mukul Dev]], [[Sardar Sohi]], [[Mouni Roy]], [[Mandy Takhar]], [[Shraddha Arya]], [[Pritam]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]], [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]\n| native_name_lang = pb\n}}\n\n'''Tejinder \"Babbu\" Maan''',<ref name=\"birth\"/> is an [[India]]n singer-songwriter, [[actor]] and [[film producer]]. Most of his artistic work focuses on [[Music of Punjab|Punjabi music]] and [[Punjabi cinema|films]].\n\n==Early life==\nMaan was raised in [[Khant, Punjab|Khant Maanpur]] in the [[Fatehgarh Sahib district]] of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India.<ref name=\"birth\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann injured while shooting|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110302/main6.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:Babbu Maan Vancouver 2010.jpg|thumb|Maan performing live in 2010]]\n\nMaan's main target audience is the [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]-speaking population of the world. Since 1999, he has released eight studio albums and six compilation albums; has written screenplays for, acted in and produced Punjabi films; and has contributed significantly to regional and [[Bollywood]] film soundtracks. Maan is the ambassador for ''One Hope, One Chance'', a non-profit organisation based out of Punjab.<ref>{{cite web|title=I Believe I've Matured|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/punjab/chandigarh/i-believe-i-ve-matured/article1-1089521.aspx|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nBabbu Maan recorded his first album ''Sajjan Rumaal De Geya'' in 1997<ref name=\"birth\"/> but revised and re-released most of the songs in his subsequent albums. Maan's first official debut album ''Tu Meri Miss India'' was released in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu's maiden album released|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99nov07/cth2.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref><ref name=\"Babbu Maan back with Saun Di Jhadi\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan back with Saun Di Jhadi|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010313/chd.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Babbu Maan released his third album ''Saaun Di Jhadi'',<ref name=\"Babbu Maan back with Saun Di Jhadi\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann case adjourned|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010629/cth2.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref> featuring songs such as ''Chan Chanani'', ''Raat Guzarlayi'', ''Dil Ta Pagal Hai'', ''Ishq'', ''Kabza'' and ''Touch Wood'', and in 2003, he wrote and sang for his first film soundtrack ''[[Hawayein (2003 film)|Hawayein]]'' where he worked alongside Indian playback singers [[Sukhwinder Singh]] and [[Jaspinder Narula]]. Maan released his fourth album ''Ohi Chann Ohi Rataan'' in 2004, followed by ''Pyaas'' in 2005, one of the best-selling Punjabi albums of the time.<ref name=\"Babbu Maan presents Talaash\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan presents Talaash|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/music/Babbu-Maan-presents-Talaash/articleshow/18827523.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> In 2007, Maan released his first Hindi album entitled ''Mera Gham'', and in 2009, his first religious album ''[[Singh Better Than King]]''.<ref name=\"Babbu Maan presents Talaash\"/> A song from the latter, ''Baba Nanak'', a reaction to fake saints and preachers in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], caused various debates about the growing phenomenon in the state.<ref name=\"Chandigarh News\">{{cite web|title=\"No one can compel us to write or write off our songs\" Babbu Mann & Bhagwant Mann|url=http://khabarchandigarh.blogspot.co.uk/2009/12/no-one-can-compel-us-to-write-or-write.html|publisher=Chandigarh News|date=11 December 2009}}</ref> On 4 July 2013, Maan released ''Talaash: In Search Of Soul'', his first Punjabi commercial album after eight years.<ref name=\"Babbu Maan presents Talaash\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=I believe I've matured|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/punjab/chandigarh/i-believe-i-ve-matured/article1-1089521.aspx|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In 2015, the album named ''Itihaas'' was released and in 2018 ''Ik C Pagal'' was released.\n\nThroughout his career, Maan has released a number of singles from various compilation albums.\n\nIn addition to ''[[Hawayein (2003 film)|Hawayein]]'', Babbu Maan has sung in Punjabi films ''Waagah'' and ''Dil Tainu Karda Ae Pyar'' as well as for [[Bollywood]] productions ''[[Vaada Raha]]'', ''[[Crook (film)|Crook]]'', ''[[Saheb, Biwi Aur Gangster]]'', ''[[Titoo MBA]]'', and ''[[31st October (film)|31st October]]''.\n\nBabbu Maan has performed in shows across Asia, [[Australasia]],<ref name=\"www.justpanjabi.com\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan on Australia-New Zealand Tour in September|url=http://www.justpanjabi.com/2011/07/babbu-maan-on-australia-new-zealand.html|publisher=www.justpanjabi.com}}</ref> Europe,<ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann questions Lala Lajpat Rai's martyrdom|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/babbu-mann-questions-lala-lajpat-rais-martyrdom_634631.html|publisher=Zee News|date=17 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu's Lajpat song strums anger|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Babbus-Lajpat-song-strums-anger/articleshow/6052502.cms?referral=PM|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> North America and the Middle East. In 2014, Maan was a winner of four World Music Awards: World's Best Indian Male Artist, World's Best Indian Live Act, World's Best Indian Entertainer and World's Best Indian Album for Talaash: In Search of Soul.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Punjabi-singer-Babbu-Maan-to-venture-into-Bollywood/articleshow/45688590.cms|title=Punjabi singer Babbu Maan to venture into Bollywood|last=Kotwani|first=Hiren|date=31 December 2014|work=[[Times of India]]|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nMaan also won two [[Awards for world music#daf BAMA MUSIC AWARDS|daf BAMA Music Awards]] Germany in 2017.\n\n===Films===\nBabbu Maan debuted in a supporting role in ''[[Hawayein (2003 film)|Hawayein]]'',<ref name=\"birth\"/> a 2003 film based on the [[1984 anti-Sikh riots]]. Although banned in India, the film was a success overseas.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} In 2006, Maan starred in his first Punjabi film as the main lead in ''Rabb Ne Banaiyan Jodiean''. Dissatisfied with certain scenes and the fate of the film, Maan returned to form in 2008 with ''Hashar (A Love Story)''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan's Hashar|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20080615/ttlife1.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bollywood Previews|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/content/articles/2008/07/18/bollywood_previews_hashar_feature.shtml|publisher=BBC Shropshire}}</ref><ref name=\"Reel Crusade\">{{cite web|title=Reel Crusade|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101025/ttlife1.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref> He has since written, produced and acted in his own films ''[[Ekam]]'',<ref name=\"Chandigarh News\"/><ref name=\"Reel Crusade\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann's movie premiered|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100420/ldh1.htm#19|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref> ''[[Hero Hitler in Love]]''<ref name=\"birth\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Studies will never take backseat|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120421/ldh1.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref><ref name=\"www.justpanjabi.com\"/> and ''[[Desi Romeos]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Romeos' musical bonanza|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news-and-interviews/Desi-Romeos-musical-bonanza/articleshow/13030978.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> Babbu Maan is a partner in ''Maan Films Pvt. Ltd'',<ref name=\"birth\"/> and in 2010, constructed a film set called ''Ishqpura'' in his native village. In 2018, he acted in the film ''[[Banjara (film)|Banjara]]'' which is based on the life of [[truck driver]]s.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 105%;\" class=sortable  +\n |- bgcolor=\"#AAAAACCCCDDDDD\" align=\"centre\"\n ! Year\n ! Album\n ! Record Label\n ! Music Director\n ! Lyrics\n |-\n | 1998\n | ''Sajjan Rumal De Geya''\n | rowspan=\"2\"|Catrack\n | rowspan=\"2\"|[[Surinder Bachan]]\n | rowspan=\"10\"|Babbu Maan\n |-\n | 1999\n | ''Tu Meri Miss India''\n |-\n | 2001\n | ''Saaun Di Jhadi''\n | rowspan=\"3\"|[[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n | [[Jaidev Kumar]]\n |-\n | 2004{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n | ''Ohi Chann Ohi Rataan''\n | rowspan=\"7\"|Babbu Maan\n |-\n | 2005\n | ''Pyass: In Search of Destiny''\n |-\n | 2007\n | ''Mera Gham''\n | rowspan=\"2\"|Point Zero\n |-\n | 2009\n | ''[[Singh Better Than King]]''\n |-\n | 20