| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2014 || ''Baaz'' ||{{yes}} || {{yes}}||{{yes}}  ||{{yes}} ||{{yes}} || || Punjabi\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016 || ''[[31st October (film)|31st October]]'' || || ||{{yes}}  || || || || Bollywood Movie\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2018\n|| ''[[Banjara: The Truck Driver|Banjara]]'' || {{yes}} ||||{{yes}} ||{{yes}} ||{{yes}} || || Punjabi\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{facebook|id=babbumaan}}\n*{{Instagram|id=babbumaaninsta}}\n*{{Twitter|id=@babbumaan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maan, Babbu}}\n[[Category:Punjabi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Punjabi cinema]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Indian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Punjabi music]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian singer-songwriter, actor and film producer}}\n{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Babbu Maan\n| image            = Babbu Maan Baarish Ke Bahaane (cropped).jpg\n| image_size       = 150px\n| caption          = Maan launching \"Baarish Ke Bahaane\"\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = <!-- Please do not add without a published reliable source. -->\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_place      = [[Khant Maanpur]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], India<ref name=\"birth\"/>\n| genre            = [[Folk music of Punjab|Folk]], [[Bhangra (popular music)|Bhangra]], Pop, [[Ghazal]]s\n| occupation       = Singer, lyricist, music director, actor, producer, screenwriter\n| years_active     = 1997\u2013present\n| label            = Catrack, [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]], Point Zero, [[Eros International]], Swag Music, Speed Records, [[Zee Music Company]], [[Sony Music India|Sony Music]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Jaspinder Narula]], [[Monty Sharma]], [[Jaidev Kumar]], [[Harjit Harman]], [[Harbhajan Mann]], [[Bhagwant Maan]], [[Gurdas Maan]], [[Mukul Dev]], [[Sardar Sohi]], [[Mouni Roy]], [[Mandy Takhar]], [[Shraddha Arya]], [[Pritam]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]], [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]\n| native_name_lang = pb\n}}\n\n'''Tejinder \"Babbu\" Maan''',<ref name=\"birth\"/> is an [[India]]n singer-songwriter, [[actor]] and [[film producer]]. Most of his artistic work focuses on [[Music of Punjab|Punjabi music]] and [[Punjabi cinema|films]].\n\n==Early life==\nMaan was raised in [[Khant, Punjab|Khant Maanpur]] in the [[Fatehgarh Sahib district]] of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India.<ref name=\"birth\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann injured while shooting|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110302/main6.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[File:Babbu Maan Vancouver 2010.jpg|thumb|Maan performing live in 2010]]\n\nMaan's main target audience is the [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]-speaking population of the world. Since 1999, he has released eight studio albums and six compilation albums; has written screenplays for, acted in and produced Punjabi films; and has contributed significantly to regional and [[Bollywood]] film soundtracks. Maan is the ambassador for ''One Hope, One Chance'', a non-profit organisation based out of Punjab.<ref>{{cite web|title=I Believe I've Matured|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/punjab/chandigarh/i-believe-i-ve-matured/article1-1089521.aspx|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nBabbu Maan recorded his first album ''Sajjan Rumaal De Geya'' in 1997<ref name=\"birth\"/> but revised and re-released most of the songs in his subsequent albums. Maan's first official debut album ''Tu Meri Miss India'' was released in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu's maiden album released|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99nov07/cth2.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref><ref name=\"Babbu Maan back with Saun Di Jhadi\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan back with Saun Di Jhadi|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010313/chd.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Babbu Maan released his third album ''Saaun Di Jhadi'',<ref name=\"Babbu Maan back with Saun Di Jhadi\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann case adjourned|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010629/cth2.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref> featuring songs such as ''Chan Chanani'', ''Raat Guzarlayi'', ''Dil Ta Pagal Hai'', ''Ishq'', ''Kabza'' and ''Touch Wood'', and in 2003, he wrote and sang for his first film soundtrack ''[[Hawayein]]'' where he worked alongside Indian playback singers [[Sukhwinder Singh]] and [[Jaspinder Narula]]. Maan released his fourth album ''Ohi Chann Ohi Rataan'' in 2004, followed by ''Pyaas'' in 2005, one of the best-selling Punjabi albums of the time.<ref name=\"Babbu Maan presents Talaash\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan presents Talaash|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/punjabi/music/Babbu-Maan-presents-Talaash/articleshow/18827523.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> In 2007, Maan released his first Hindi album entitled ''Mera Gham'', and in 2009, his first religious album ''[[Singh Better Than King]]''.<ref name=\"Babbu Maan presents Talaash\"/> A song from the latter, ''Baba Nanak'', a reaction to fake saints and preachers in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], caused various debates about the growing phenomenon in the state.<ref name=\"Chandigarh News\">{{cite web|title=\"No one can compel us to write or write off our songs\" Babbu Mann & Bhagwant Mann|url=http://khabarchandigarh.blogspot.co.uk/2009/12/no-one-can-compel-us-to-write-or-write.html|publisher=Chandigarh News|date=11 December 2009}}</ref> On 4 July 2013, Maan released ''Talaash: In Search Of Soul'', his first Punjabi commercial album after eight years.<ref name=\"Babbu Maan presents Talaash\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=I believe I've matured|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/punjab/chandigarh/i-believe-i-ve-matured/article1-1089521.aspx|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In 2015, the album named ''Itihaas'' was released and in 2018 ''Ik C Pagal'' was released.\n\nThroughout his career, Maan has released a number of singles from various compilation albums.\n\nIn addition to ''[[Hawayein]]'', Babbu Maan has sung in Punjabi films ''Waagah'' and ''Dil Tainu Karda Ae Pyar'' as well as for [[Bollywood]] productions ''[[Vaada Raha]]'', ''[[Crook (film)|Crook]]'', ''[[Saheb, Biwi Aur Gangster]]'', ''[[Titoo MBA]]'', and ''[[31st October (film)|31st October]]''.\n\nBabbu Maan has performed in shows across Asia, [[Australasia]],<ref name=\"www.justpanjabi.com\">{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan on Australia-New Zealand Tour in September|url=http://www.justpanjabi.com/2011/07/babbu-maan-on-australia-new-zealand.html|publisher=www.justpanjabi.com}}</ref> Europe,<ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann questions Lala Lajpat Rai's martyrdom|url=http://zeenews.india.com/home/babbu-mann-questions-lala-lajpat-rais-martyrdom_634631.html|publisher=Zee News|date=17 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu's Lajpat song strums anger|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Babbus-Lajpat-song-strums-anger/articleshow/6052502.cms?referral=PM|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> North America and the Middle East. In 2014, Maan was a winner of four World Music Awards: World's Best Indian Male Artist, World's Best Indian Live Act, World's Best Indian Entertainer and World's Best Indian Album for Talaash: In Search of Soul.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Punjabi-singer-Babbu-Maan-to-venture-into-Bollywood/articleshow/45688590.cms|title=Punjabi singer Babbu Maan to venture into Bollywood|last=Kotwani|first=Hiren|date=31 December 2014|work=[[Times of India]]|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nMaan also won two [[Awards for world music#daf BAMA MUSIC AWARDS|daf BAMA Music Awards]] Germany in 2017.\n\n===Films===\nBabbu Maan debuted in a supporting role in ''[[Hawayein]]'',<ref name=\"birth\"/> a 2003 film based on the [[1984 anti-Sikh riots]]. Although banned in India, the film was a success overseas.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} In 2006, Maan starred in his first Punjabi film as the main lead in ''Rabb Ne Banaiyan Jodiean''. Dissatisfied with certain scenes and the fate of the film, Maan returned to form in 2008 with ''Hashar (A Love Story)''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Maan's Hashar|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20080615/ttlife1.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bollywood Previews|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/content/articles/2008/07/18/bollywood_previews_hashar_feature.shtml|publisher=BBC Shropshire}}</ref><ref name=\"Reel Crusade\">{{cite web|title=Reel Crusade|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101025/ttlife1.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref> He has since written, produced and acted in his own films ''[[Ekam]]'',<ref name=\"Chandigarh News\"/><ref name=\"Reel Crusade\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Babbu Mann's movie premiered|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100420/ldh1.htm#19|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref> ''[[Hero Hitler in Love]]''<ref name=\"birth\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Studies will never take backseat|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120421/ldh1.htm|publisher=The Tribune, Chandigarh}}</ref><ref name=\"www.justpanjabi.com\"/> and ''[[Desi Romeos]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title='Desi Romeos' musical bonanza|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news-and-interviews/Desi-Romeos-musical-bonanza/articleshow/13030978.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> Babbu Maan is a partner in ''Maan Films Pvt. Ltd'',<ref name=\"birth\"/> and in 2010, constructed a film set called ''Ishqpura'' in his native village. In 2018, he acted in the film ''[[Banjara (film)|Banjara]]'' which is based on the life of [[truck driver]]s.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\